@node Introduction

      @{b}I N T R O D U C T I O N@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      @{b}MerlinMPEG@{ub} decodes and  displays  MPEG-1  encoded  bitstreams  on
      Amigas with the @{b}Merlin@{ub} graphics board. The player will  create  a
      new screen or Picture-In-Picture (PIP) window, display  the  bit-
      stream, and exit.
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node Requirements

      @{b}R E Q U I R E M E N T S@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   AmigaOS 2.04 or higher,
      o   Merlin Graphic Accelerator with HRG System Version 38,
      o   MC68020 CPU or higher.
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node CLIUsage

      @{b}C L I   U S A G E@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      @{b}FORMAT@{ub}

          MerlinMPEG File @{" PackedDisplay " Link PackedOpt} @{" TargaDisplay " Link TargaOpt}
          @{" XgaDisplay " Link XgaOpt} @{" RgbDisplay " Link RgbOpt} @{" Gray " Link GrayOpt} @{" PipWindow " Link PipOpt} @{" NoDisplay " Link NoDisplayOpt}
          @{" NoBFrames " Link NoBFramesOpt} @{" NoPFrames " Link NoPFramesOpt} @{" LumRange <n> " Link LumRangeOpt} @{" CrRange <n> " Link CrRangeOpt}
          @{" CbRange <n> " Link CbRangeOpt} @{" HrgRender " Link HrgRenderOpt} @{" Loop " Link LoopOpt} @{" Quiet " Link QuietOpt}

      @{b}TEMPLATE@{ub}

          File/A,PD=PackedDisplay/S,TD=TargaDisplay/S,XD=XgaDisplay/S,
          RD=RgbDisplay/S,G=Gray/S,ND=NoDisplay/S,PW=PipWindow/S,
          NB=NoBFrames/S,NP=NoPFrames/S,LU=LumRange/K/N,CR=CrRange/K/N,
          CB=CbRange/K/N,HR=HrgRender/S,L=Loop/S,Q=Quiet/S

      @{" Examples " Link Examples}
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node WBUsage

      @{b}W O R K B E N C H   U S A G E@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      Double-clicking on the MerlinMPEG icon will bring up a requester
      asking for the MPEG-1 stream. The options are read from the icon's
      tool types.

      The following @{b}TOOLTYPES@{ub} are available:

      o   @{" PACKEDDISPLAY " Link PackedOpt}, @{" TARGADISPLAY " Link TargaOpt}, @{" XGADISPLAY " Link XgaOpt},
          @{" RGBDISPLAY " Link RgbOpt} or @{" GRAY " Link GrayOpt}
      o   @{" PIPWINDOW " Link PipOpt}
      o   @{" NOPFRAMES " Link NoPFramesOpt}
      o   @{" NOBFRAMES " Link NoBFramesOpt}
      o   @{" LUMRANGE=<n> " Link LumRangeOpt}
      o   @{" CRRANGE=<n> " Link CrRangeOpt}
      o   @{" CBRANGE=<n> " Link CbRangeOpt}
      o   @{" HRGRENDER " Link HrgRenderOpt}
      o   @{" LOOP " Link LoopOpt}
      o   @{" DIRECTORY=<s>" Link DirOpt}
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node PackedOpt

      @{b}P A C K E D D I S P L A Y@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   Display Mode     : 8 bit Color Screen
      o   Number of Colors : 240 (2 * 8 reserved)
      o   Dither Mode      : Fast Ordered Dither
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node TargaOpt

      @{b}T A R G A D I S P L A Y@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   Display Mode     : 15 bit HiColor Screen
      o   Number of Colors : 32.768
      o   Dither Mode      : None
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node XgaOpt

      @{b}X G A D I S P L A Y@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   Display Mode     : 16 bit HiColor Screen
      o   Number of Colors : 65.536
      o   Dither Mode      : None
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node RgbOpt

      @{b}R G B D I S P L A Y@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   Display Mode     : 24 bit TrueColor Screen
      o   Number of Colors : 16.777.216
      o   Dither Mode      : None
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node PipOpt

      @{b}P I P W I N D O W@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   Display Mode     : 8 bit PIP Window on Merlin Screen
      o   Number of Colors : 240 (2 * 8 reserved)
      o   See Also         : @{" GRAY " Link GrayOpt}
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node GrayOpt

      @{b}G R A Y@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   Display Mode     : 8 bit Grayscale Screen or PIP Window
      o   Number of Colors : 240 (2 * 8 reserved)
      o   Dither Mode      : None
      o   See Also         : @{" PIPWINDOW " Link PipOpt}
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node NoPFramesOpt

      @{b}N O P F R A M E S@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   Function         : Causes the player to ignore and not display
                             any P frames.
      o   See Also         : @{" NOBFRAME " Link NoBFramesOpt}
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node NoBFramesOpt

      @{b}N O B F R A M E S@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   Function         : Causes the player to ignore and not display
                             any B frames.
      o   See Also         : @{" NOPFRAME " Link NoPFramesOpt}
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node LumRangeOpt

      @{b}L U M R A N G E = < n >@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   Function         : Sets the number of colors assigned to the
                             luminance component when dithering the image.
                             The product of LumRange, CrRange and CbRange
                             should be less than 241.
      o   Legal Values     : 2 ... 240
      o   See Also         : @{" CRRANGE " Link CrRangeOpt}, @{" CBRANGE " Link CbRangeOpt}
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node CrRangeOpt

      @{b}C R R A N G E = < n >@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   Function         : Sets the number of colors assigned to the
                             red component of the chrominance range when
                             dithering the image.
      o   Legal Values     : 1 ... 120
      o   See Also         : @{" LUMRANGE " Link LumRangeOpt}, @{" CBRANGE " Link CbRangeOpt}
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node CbRangeOpt

      @{b}C B R A N G E = < n >@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   Function         : Sets the number of colors assigned to the
                             blue component of the chrominance range.
      o   Legal Values     : 1 ... 120
      o   See Also         : @{" LUMRANGE " Link LumRangeOpt}, @{" CRRANGE " Link CrRangeOpt}
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node HrgRenderOpt

      @{b}H R G R E N D E R@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   Function         : Use HRGRender.library syscalls when drawing
                             the image.
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node LoopOpt

      @{b}L O O P@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   Function         : Makes the player loop back to the beginning
                             after reaching the end.
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node QuietOpt

      @{b}Q U I E T@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   Function         : Supresses printing of timing information,
                             and most error messages.
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node NoDisplayOpt

      @{b}N O D I S P L A Y@{ub} :
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   Function         : The player does not dither and display,
                             usually used for testing and timing
                             purposes.
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node DirOpt

      @{b}D I R E C T O R Y = < s >@{ub} :
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   Function         : The string <s> defines the default directory
                             for the MPEG animation files.
      o   Legal Values     : A valid amiga device or directory name.
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node Examples

      @{b}E X A M P L E S@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      1> @{b}MerlinMPEG XgaDisplay canyon.mpg@{ub}

      Show the MPEG animation "canyon.mpg" on a HiColor Merlin screen.

      1> @{b}MerlinMPEG g pw debbieharry.mpg@{ub}

      Open a PIP and show "debbieharry.mpg" in a grayscale window.

      Some @{b}Speed@{ub} examples on my Amiga 2000 with GForce040/33MHz,
      KickStart 40.63 and WorkBench 40.42 :

      MPEG Animation   | Size in |          Avg. Frames / Sec
                       | pixels  | low   high  true  gray  pip  graypip
      -----------------+---------+-------------------------------------
      canyon.mpg       | 144*112 | 20.0  18.9  17.8  34.8  20.2  27.7
      pirates.mpg      | 160*120 | 11.5  11.6  11.1  19.2  11.6  15.1
      debbieharry.mpg  | 160*128 | 10.5  10.8  10.3  18.4  10.6  14.0
      tennis.mpg       | 352*240 |  3.6   3.4   3.2   6.0   3.6   4.9
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node Notes

      @{b}N O T E S@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

        The player expects @{b}MPEG-1@{ub} video streams  only.  It  can  not
        handle  multiplexed MPEG streams or video+audio streams. The
        player uses the paris entropy coding  table  set  (which  we
        believe  to  be the MPEG-1 standard), but can not handle any
        bitstreams that use the "berlin" entropy coding  table  set.
        Berlin  data  is  relatively  rare so there shouldn't be too
        much to worry about here, but be  aware  of  the  difference
        when looking for streams to play.

        Some streams do not end with the proper  sequence  end  code
        and  will probably generate an "Improper sequence end code."
        error when done playing.

        This player can play @{b}XING@{ub} data files.  Be  aware  that  XING
        makes  no use of temporal redundancy or motion vector infor-
        mation. In other words, they do not use any P or B frames in
        their  streams. Instead, XING data is simply a sequence of I
        frames. Since I frames take significantly longer to  decode,
        performance of the player using XING data is not representa-
        tive of the player's ability.
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

@node Bugs

      @{b}K N O W N  B U G S@{ub}
      _________________________________________________________________

      o   hrAllocSecondView() produces an Enforcer Hit with
          HRGSystem.library < 39.21.

      o   PIP works incorrect on scrollable screen.
      _________________________________________________________________
@endnode

